            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born and raised in the foggy avenues of San Francisco's Richmond District, Mei-Lin Novak is a product of two distinct worlds. Her mother, a stoic and hardworking immigrant from Hong Kong, and her father, a warm, second-generation Polish-American carpenter, created a home filled with both quiet duty and boisterous affection. Growing up, Mei-Lin became an expert translator not just of language, but of unspoken emotions, a skill that would later define her career.\n\nInitially, she attended UC Berkeley with plans for a more \"practical\" business degree, a nod to her mother\u2019s wishes for security. However, her father's sudden death from a heart attack during her sophomore year became a pivotal turning point. Navigating her family\u2019s disparate ways of grieving\u2014her mother\u2019s silent endurance, her own overwhelming sorrow\u2014ignited a profound interest in the human psyche. She switched her major and later earned a doctorate in Clinical Psychology from the Wright Institute.\n\nIn her late twenties, she married Mark Novak, a fellow academic, and they had a son, Leo. For nearly two decades, she balanced her demanding work at a city hospital with raising her child. The marriage ended amicably ten years ago, a conscious uncoupling that allowed them to co-parent effectively. She kept the name Novak, a testament to the family they built.\n\nNow at 51, Mei-Lin\u2019s life has settled into a purposeful rhythm. She lives in a cozy Noe Valley apartment and takes the J-Church MUNI line to her private practice near Dolores Park. Her days are spent guiding clients through trauma, anxiety, and depression. Leo is now away at college, leaving her with a quiet space she fills with long walks through Glen Canyon Park, dinners with a small circle of trusted friends, and attempts at perfecting her mother\u2019s dumpling recipe.\n\nHer connection to San Francisco is bone-deep; the city is the backdrop to every joy and loss. Looking forward, Mei-Lin dreams not of radical change, but of deepening her impact. She aspires to travel through Asia and Eastern Europe, tracing her ancestry, and harbors a quiet hope of writing a book exploring the intersection of cultural identity and mental wellness\u2014a tribute to the two worlds she has always called home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers being nine, at their kitchen table in the Richmond. Her father, booming with laughter, told a joke that didn't quite land. Her mother\u2019s face remained a mask of polite stillness, but Mei-Lin saw the flicker of confusion in her eyes. Without a word, Mei-Lin leaned over and quietly rephrased the punchline in Cantonese. Her mother\u2019s lips curled into a small, rare smile. In that moment, she wasn't just translating words; she was bridging worlds. It was her first, unspoken job, the foundation of a lifetime of listening.\n\n2.\nThe phone call came to her Berkeley dorm. Her mother\u2019s voice was flat, devoid of the emotion that was exploding inside Mei-Lin\u2019s own chest. \"Your father is gone.\" Later, sitting in the silence of their family home, she watched her mother meticulously clean, a ritual of silent endurance. Mei-Lin\u2019s own grief felt loud and messy. This profound disconnect\u2014this chasm between their ways of mourning\u2014ignited a desperate need to understand the architecture of human sorrow. It was the moment she knew business was not her path.\n\n3.\nShe recalls a sun-drenched afternoon, a rare gift in the city. Leo, maybe five, was on the swings at Dolores Park, his little legs pumping furiously. \"Higher, Mama, higher!\" he squealed, his laughter echoing against the skyline. For that moment, the weight of her patients' trauma and the endless juggling act simply dissolved. There was only the warmth of the sun and the joyful arc of her son\u2019s flight. This memory became an anchor, a reminder of the simple, fierce love that fueled all the difficult work.\n\n4.\nThey sat on the back deck of their Noe Valley house, the one she would keep. It wasn\u2019t a fight, but a final, shared acknowledgment. Mark reached across the small table and took her hand. \"We built a good family, Mei,\" he said, his voice thick with two decades of shared history. A profound sadness settled over her, but it was clean, without bitterness. They were not failing, but choosing a new shape for their family. It was a painful, respectful closing of a chapter, a testament to the son they adored.\n\n5.\nLast Tuesday, after a long day at her practice, the silence in her apartment felt immense. Leo was gone. She stood in her kitchen, flour dusting her hands, attempting her mother\u2019s dumplings. The folds were clumsy, not yet right. A wave of loneliness washed over her, sharp and sudden. But then, it receded, leaving a quiet resolve. She was here, in this city that held all her ghosts and joys, learning to perfect a legacy, finding comfort in the solitude and the muscle memory of her heritage."
